FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE HCD PICK-OFF ON THE PD-4. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE TURNED OFF   SECURED THE BELT, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 4 MINUTES A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING THE PROPER PPE AND WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 6 POLY 2-LITER DISPENSER/CONTAINERS WAS SLIGHTLY AJAR, CAUSING APPROX. 12 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS/IN BURSTING TEST.

FRA HM Inspector Steven Myers found HM tank car PROX 47160 placarded class3, UN 3295, loaded with UN3295 Hydrocarbons, Liquid, N.O.S. class 3, PG 1, (natural gasoline) to be venting at the vacuum relief device.  This was reported to BPRR management and SPSI was dispatched by Buffalo & Pittsburgh Railroad (Rita Mager) to investigate and make certified permanent repairs.  Shipper MarkWest Energy, Shawn Dunkle notified.  Upon inspection, SPSI determined defective vacuum relief device and they did not have part, so made temporary repairs (gasket) to eliminate any venting possibility.  Shipper notified car owner, Gunvor, who hired Rescar to make repairs.

On 1/5/24 at approximately 10:00 AM, Operators were loading ethanol from railcar MUI-X 730192 into Petroleum Carriers trailer 9301. While loading a scheduled 1400 gallons into compartment 2(capacity 2500 gallons), product. was released from the overflow tubes at the rear of the trailer. The pump 0meter read 1272 gallons at the time of the release. An estimated 100 gallons impacted the asphalt. Product evaporated, there is no cleanup material to be disposed of. All appropriate personnel were notified of the incident. Overfill protection on the pump was disabled by the loaders. Driver failed to advise loaders that there was product remaining in the compartment being loaded.
column170: Pump used was taken out of service as the overfill protection system was not compatible with all trailers being loaded. Overfill protection switches have been locked out on all pumps to prevent disabling by employees for any reason. Employees have been retrained to never bypass a safety device and to report all equipment problems it mangement immediately.

column169: PVS Transportation driver was unloading the product into the customer's tank while a customer's employee was monitoring the gauge on the tank {because the gauge was not visible from the truck). The customer's employee did not notify our driver to stop the flow of product until the tank started overflowing. The tank was overflowing into containment for approximately 8 seconds. The driver and operator at the facility cleaned up the spill by using spill pads to soak up and vinegar to neutralize the caustic soda. The gauge on the tank was stuck on 3/4 full.
column170: PVS sent a operations specialist to the location and determined the gauge on the tank was not registering the accurate quantity in the tank. The gauge was replaced and is now measuring accurately. PVS Safety Team communicated with the customer on identifying when the gauge is not moving during the unloading process, to stop the flow of product until the level of product in the tank can be accurately determined.

On January 17, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of lactic acid was damaged in transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the lactic acid- impacted trailer to the extent practicable. Crews transferred the remaining product from the damaged tote to a new one. The damaged tote and all impacted debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and R+L personnel took possession of the waste.

column169: While boarding flight 149 JFK to GND. The FO and CA were waiting for refueling to be completed before doing the before start checked to the line. The F3, came in the cockpit and said there was a “medical issue” he then corrected and said ”safety issue in the jetway”. The CA was walking into the galley was told it was a bag fire in the jetway.  When he stepped into the jetway, he observed a wet bag, 2 empty water bottles, and fire extinguisher, next to an open bag.  It had a  blue battery disconnected from the bag. The F1 was watching over it with fire gloves. The CA then asked all in the jetway (starting to get crowded) if fire rescue was notified and was told ops knows about it. He immediately went into the cockpit and called ground operations to let them know they were had a bag fire in the jetway that appeared to be out. He also mentioned that he believed ops had informed Port authority but would confirm. He called OPS on the radio and they knew. He asked them to call the Port Authority to have the bag looked at. They said they would.  On his way back to the jetway he noticed all the customers were in their seats he checked on the bag. No fire and then made a PA to let the customers know all was safe and what had happened.  After things settled down it became clear to me what an amazing job the Flight attendants did. The F1 said she observed the customer walking down the jetway rolling a smoking bag. She stoped the customer prevented the bag from getting on the aircraft and called for safety team on the PA. She and the team went into action and by the time I got to the jetway, they had the fire out the battery cooled with water and the customers in their seats. Obviously the aircraft passageway was initially clogged with bags customers etc. that was cleared and the F3 got to the cockpit to let us know about the issue. I can’t say enough about how well the flight attendants did.   The suitcase was found to contain a medical refrigerator, manufactured by North Sciences.  The battery connected to the refrigerator was a 120 wH, Lithium Ion Battery.  It's only markings were as follows: Stirling Engine Li-ion Battery Model: JCB2405A Rated: 24V-5000mAh-120Wh Date: 2021-7 All other markings were in foreign language.  The bag also contained a Power Supply Unit, manufacturer unknown.  It had a Lithium Ion battery rated at 257.52 Wh.  It did not go into thermal runaway and did not contribute to the event.  Both items were confiscated and placed on internal reports DGR53-24 (battery) and DGR64-24 (Power Supply).
column170: The Inflight Crewmembers following the instructions in their manual and were able to resloved the situation quickly.  We are reviewing the incident to determine if a containment bag would have helped the situation further.

On 01/04/2024, at 1336 hours, personnel at the CSX yard in Selkirk, New York, reported product leaking from inside the valve box of car LTCX 1902, a tank car loaded with Argon, refrigerated liquid.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Linde Inc., was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-0104-00121). David Scoons, a CSX Senior Manager of Hazardous Materials, responded to the incident and determined the cause of the release was a loose coupler fitting on a gauge panel feed line.  Response personnel tightened the loose coupler fitting and stopped the release.  The shipper’s representative, Timothy Lavallee (716-225-0242), was notified of the condition found and the corrective actions taken.

The accident is still under investigation to determine the cause.  What we know is the vehicle veered to the right leaving the interstate and rolling multiple times.  Due to the rollover, a 2 inch pipe on the back end of the tank was broken off causing the loss of ammonia.  Carbon Count FD, WY State Police and EMT's responded to the scene.  I80 was closed for an estimated 5 hours, favorable wind direction allowed the interstate to reopen.  We dispatched our local plant manager to the scene to help determine the severity of the leak.  Once we received information back, it was determined to tarp and cover the release to help contain the fugitive vapors near the truck.  Our Field Service team was activated and sent to the site to remove the remaining liquid ammonia from the truck to allow for a safe recovery of the vehicle by the tow company.
column170: Due to this accident still being under investigation to determine a cause, specific changes have not yet been suggested.  We did immediately initiate internal Bobtail Truck training to review actions to prevent bobtail rollovers.

On January 30th, 2024, at 1346 hours, personnel at the CSX Boyles Terminal in Birmingham, Alabama, reported a suspect odor from an inbound train.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSX emergency response contractor, and Davy Ferguson, a CSX Manager of Hazardous Materials, responded to investigate.  Upon investigation the area, response personnel discovered GATX 60194, a loaded tank car of Sulfur, Molten, was leaking vapor from the manway cover due to (1) of (6) manway cover bolts being less than tool tight. The car was isolated and the shipper, Contango Resources, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-01-30-00168).  Response personnel properly secured the manway cover and stopped the release.  The defect found and correction actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Ross Goff (307-840-1078).

The drum was not packaged correctly. On January 17, 2024, one (1) 50-pound bag of UN3262 was torn in transit and released approximately twenty-five (25) pounds of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration (ER) to remediate the site. ER personnel utilized absorbents, hand tools, and a vacuum unit to remediate the powder-impacted trailer. All waste was collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums staged at the terminal for future disposal.

01/16/24 at 08:55 hours, an FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector working in the CSX Selkirk Yard reported loaded tank car UTLX 209284, Alcohols NOS, leaking from the bottom outlet valve (BOV). The car was isolated and the shipper, Cargill, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-0116-0040). HEPACO, a CSX Emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and confirmed the initial report of a leaking BOV. Upon further inspection, it was determined product was leaking past the internal ball of the BOV due to a defective component.  It was also noted that due to a deteriorated gasket, the BOV’s secondary closure cap was unable to contain the leak.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper-s representative- Daniel Gernant (303-709-1653, Daniel_Gernant@cargill.com).  Contractor personnel installed a new gasket on the secondary closure cap to contain stop the release.  The car was held at Selkirk pending transload of the contents and certified repair and/or OTMA.

column169: The driver was traveling on I-71WB in KY when a passer by flagged him down. He then pulled off at the Sulfur Ky exit and inspected his load he noticed a frozen material at the back door of the trailer. The driver then grabbed some   absorbent to put down at the back of the trailer to prevent material from getting on the ground. The driver then called our emergency line at 1351ET to report the incident. The team was dispatched and arrived at 1745ET to start the clean up. The team dawned the proper PPE and proceeded to clean up the frozen material at the back of the trailer. There was aprxemetly 1-2oz that made it to the ground everything else was contained to  the trailer and absorbent wags. Once that was cleaned they opened the trailer and found material frozen on the floor and proceeded to clean it up. They then gained access to the drum that was about half way in the trailer and found that the bottom of the drum has approximately 1in crack at the bottom. The team put the damaged container into a salvage drum along with absorbents used to clean up the material. The team was able to finish the clean up around 0100ET.
column170: We believe that a nail from the pallet may have been the cause of the damage to the drum. We will be reviewing the use of pallets and to make sure they are in good condition with no nails sticking up as to catch the container and causing a puncture or rubbing a hole in it.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XCO experienced a UN3264 Kroff KR-B3020 release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100-gallons of product released to an 8’ x 20’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Sodium bicarb and absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted area to clean and neutralize the release. The impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were then collected and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized into an 85-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

INNER CONTENT INSPECTION REVEALS AN AIRCRAFT PART ENCLOSED AND ZIPTIED WITHIN A PLASTIC BAG. THERE IS A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE BAG CONSISTENT WITH THE SHAPE OF THE PART INSIDE THE BAG. THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX HAS ALSO BEEN PUNCTURED SLIGHTLY CONSISTENT TO THE SAME COMPROMISED LOCATION. PAPERWORK INSIDE THE PACKAGE INDICATES THE PRODUCT AS "8120-2 FUEL OIL COOLER OIL LEAK FTN 5M3095". THE INVOICE AND THERMAL LABEL DESCRIPTION OF THE COMMODITY IS A COOLER. column169: I, John Vergis Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE, was called by the WLE Brewster Yardmaster at 0130 hrs. on 1-25-2024 for a report of leaking tank car GATZX 80031.  When I arrived to look at the car, I noticed that the car was leaking from the breadbox cover.  I removed seal #0000823 and opened the lid to find that the leak was coming from the Apollo Liquid Valve.  I saw that the valve stem nut was backed off the stem and that the valve handle was not secured tight to the stem anymore.  It looked like when someone tried to tighten the valve, that is did not close all the way because the valve handle did not fit properly since it was loose.  I applied the handle back on the stem and tried closing the valve.  The valve did then close and the leak stopped.  The liquid was leaking from out of the valve plug which was not tight.  I tried to tighten the valve stem nut but I could not get it to tighten.  I backed off the nut completely and found that someone tried installing a course thread nut onto a fine thread valve stem.  That is why the nut would not tighten down onto the handle.  I then tried installing a fine thread nut and I was able to get it to tighten down.  I felt that is was a good fix.  I then removed the plug from the valve since it was leaking and found that there was no thread tape on the threads that were screwed into the valve.  There was a build up of old tape on the top portion of the threads but not on the threads that would actually seal.  Installed new thread sealant and tightened the valve plug.  I then closed the breadbox lid and inatalled new seal #0000229.  I then released the car for transportation.
column170: Better car securement procedures need followed.

Driver encountered deteriorating roadway conditions on his way to make delivery to the customer. At some point driver claims that a 3rd party driver veered into his lane causing him to take minor evasive action. This lead to loss of control when he contacted an icy road surface. The tanktruck rolled into the median where it came to rest. Ther was a rupture of a vapor valve as well as the diesel fuel tank. Luckily due to the cold weather only minor amounts of ammonia were lost through the vapor break. The police and local fire department were called to the scene to set up roadblocks and control the area.  The Huntsville, AL Hazmat team eventually made it to the site to assess the situation. It was deemed feasible to set the truck upright and tow away to a remote location for product offload and depressurization. Fugitive vapors were controlled by water application by the FD. A fuel cleanup team has been assigned to remove soil and diesel fuel as well.
column170: Rollover was due to unfortunate deterioration of conditions which is difficult to avoid. 3rd party may have played a role in the accident as well, but unfortunately there is lack of conclusive video evidence or an eyewitness to corroborate this. In future we will further promote the fact that our drivers have the last say when making a delivery as to whether it is safe or not without any repercussion. We need them to understand that no delivery is worth their own safety or the safety of the community.

column169: We transport UN 3170 Aluminum remelting by product in end dump trailers. Our driver was traveling north on 1-65 in Alabama. There had been snow and ice earlier that week. The driver came upon a multi vehicle accident. The driver attempted to slow and stop, but the vehicle got onto black ice and was unable to stop. This resulted in a collision that caused our trailer to partially over turn spilling some of the product. The divider wall prevented our trailer from completely turning over. Emergency response personal was notified, and clean up began. Alabama State Troopers have not produced an accident report as of 2/15/2024.
column170: We can only advice our drivers to take every precaution when driving in inclement weather. Going forward, we will try and deter our drivers from being on the roads in such conditions.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: A package was tendered by forwarder DHL to Qatar Airways in DFW under MAWB 157-89110081 declared as consolidation. Actual contents were medical equipment and accessories per HAWB description which contained lithium ion batteries. It was not booked as an ELI shipment as it was supposed to but had an ELI label and PSN written on package. Upon acceptance and build up GHA where house staff failed to notice the ELI label and the PSN. As a result it was manifested and forwarded as general cargo on flight QR730/24Jan DFWDOH. Upon arrival of flight in Doha, it was discovered as a undeclared battery shipment. Shipment was held in Doha until proper documents were furnished to match package contents and labeling. Report filed with local CAA.
column170: 1. All GHA warehouse staff made aware by a read& sign, to check all sides of freight upon acceptance and build-up. 2. Temporary embargo imposed on shipper until corrective and preventive measures advised to avoid recurrence.

Patriot Environmental Services was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed  that the released material impacted a 1ft- by-1ft area of the trailer floor and a 1ft-by-1ft area of the concrete parking lot and estimated that two (2) pounds  of  material  was  released  due  to  load  shift  that  damaged  one  (1)  plastic  bag.  Patriot Environmental Services personnel deployed absorbents to the impacted areas and recovered the spent material.  The  impacted  areas  were  then  treated  with  a  neutralizer.  The  spent  material  that  was recovered was containerized into one (1) 15-gallon poly drum and the damaged 50-pound plastic bag along with the remaining product was placed into one (1) additional 15-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated  waste  will  remain  onsite  until  the  waste  profile  has  been  completed  and  approved  for transport for disposal.

column169: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. Leak was discovered coming from intermodal container (trailer), while staged at facility. Area was isolated and Willoughby Fire Department was dispatched to assess the site. Willoughby FD applied absorbent pads to the affected asphalt lot and deployed absorbent boom to nearby storm drains. Clean Harbors Environmental Services was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, Clean Harbors Environmental applied additional absorbent material to the affected asphalt, inspected the nearby storm drain catch basins, and inspected the Ieaking trailer. Upon inspection, one 275gallon tote was discovered punctured at nose of trailer. Approximately 170 gallons of free product were released to the trailer floor, asphalt lot, and nearby storm drain catch basins. Clean Harbors Environmental proceeded to pH the impacted storm drains, which were returned neutral. Clean Harbors Environmental cleaned the trailer floor, wiped down adjacent freight, recovered spent absorbent material from the impacted asphalt, and emptied damaged tote. Two 55-gallon drums of free product, and 10 55-gallon drums of spent absorbent material and deanup debris were generated during the cleanup. Product was contained to an impervious surface and did not impact surface soils or state waters. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column43: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column169: On January 18, 2024, at 0200 EST, an XPO Logistics tractor trailer hauling double trailers (truck # 05328716, trailer #s 03171129, 03171874) was involved in a rollover accident due to inclement weather conditions. Immediately after the accident occurred, the roads to the site were closed due to the weather and the unit was left onsite. No drains or waterways were reported to be impacted by the release. On January 18, 2024, at 0256 EST, XPO Logistics contacted Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) to manage and oversee the above referenced incident. ERTS secured Haz-Mat Response Inc. (HMRI) to perform emergency response and remediation. On January 18, 2024, HMRI responded to the site at 1140 ET to obtain an assessment of the site. At the time, there was no visual release of material from the unit, but it was also in 5-6” of snow. Once HMRI left site, the wrecker unit showed up at approximately 1300 ET to haul the unit offsite. Initially they did not report seeing a release of material when the unit was up righted. On January 19th, HMRI mobilized to the wrecker yard to find the batteries had released approximately 50-100 gallons of battery acid to the trailer floor, walls, ceiling, and soil along the passenger side of the unit in the wrecker yard. An estimated 5-gallons of acid impacted a 26’ x 1’ area of the soil in the dirt lot. Soda ash and floor dry were deployed to the impacted trailer floor to neutralize the acid. The wrecker crew then advise to HMRI there was a loss of acid to the incident site in the soil median where the unit came to a rest. HMRI secured the unit at the wrecker’s yard and mobilized to the accident site where they confirmed an approximate 2-gallon release to a 5’ x 15’ area of the median ditch. The area was hand excavated and all impacted soil placed into a drum which was removed from site. At this point, the 7-gallons of material confirmed to impact soil/dirt was reported to the WY DEQ. On January 22, 2024, at 1100 ET, HMRI returned to the wrecker yard to complete trailer remediation. Each battery was wiped down and inspected. All 70 salvageable batteries were secured on the unit on 4 pallets to be hauled back to XPO with the unit. The trailer floor was neutralized with soda ash and floor dry, and the soil was hand excavated. A total of 213 damaged batteries were containerized into (9) 95-gallon poly drums and will attempt to be recycled. All impacted debris including the impacted floor dry, soda ash, soil, dirt, poly sheeting, cardboard, and PPE were collected and containerized into (2) 55-gallon poly and (3) 95-gallon poly drums for disposal. All waste is currently located at HMRI’s shop located in Windsor, CO pending profiling, disposal, and recycling. Please see attached photos (Appendix 2).

On January 24, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of UN2922 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately 120-gallons of product to the trailer interior, pavement below the trailer, and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Hazmat Services, Inc. (EHS) to remediate the impacted site.  EHS personnel deployed granular absorbents and a neutralizing agent to remediate the site. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into six (6) 55-gallon drums. Crews transferred the remaining product in the damaged 275-gallon tote into one (1) 275 gallon tote. All containers were staged onsite for future disposal.

column169: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While at truckstop, a leak was detected coming from trailer. Posen Fire Department was dispatched to assess. Area was isolated and Hazchem Environmental Corp was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, Hazchem applied absorbent material to the affected asphalt and inpsected the trailer. One 55-gallon drum was discovered at nose of trailer, which had been punctured by a sharp object in transit. Hazchem proceeded to offload the trailer, overpacked the damaged drum, and cleaned the trailer floor. All spent absorbents were recovered from trailer floor and affected asphalt, which were placed into two 55-gallon drums. Product was contained to an impervious surface and did not threaten to impact surface soils or state waters. Two 55-gallon drums of spent absorbents and cleanup debris, and one overpack drum, were generated during cleanup, which were transported off site pending disposal. There were no injuries or exposures reported. ,

column169: On January 16, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN3149 was crushed in transit and released approximately four (4) gallons of product to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the impacted site. column169: On the morning of January 30, 2024, a Veolia employee was at the customer site loading a drum of sulfuric acid into their trailer when the incident occurred. The Veolia employee was maneuvering the drum to the edge of the dock, however there was no dock leveler or dock plate. The employee proceeded to get the drum cart and pick up and move the drum the rest of the way when one of the forks from the drum cart pierced the drum. The customer came to assist and pumped the damaged drum into a new drum. The damaged drum was then put into an overpack. The Veolia supervisor and EHS manager responded to assist by contacting the remediation/ spill response team to respond with a neutralizer so the truck can be cleaned up and the job can resume.
column170: The Veolia EHS manager reviewed the incident with the employee and discussed a better and safer manner to maneuver the drums and use a portable dock leveler.

A Veolia employee was moving a pallet of drums onto a trailer using a forklift at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility in Kansas City. There was a slight bump as he was driving onto the trailer which resulted in one of the drums falling off the pallet being carried by the forklift. The drum had an older ring on the lid which broke as a result of the fall. Approximately 2 pounds of the waste inside the drum spilled onto the trailer floor. The spill was contained inside the trailer, was immediately cleaned up and the team replaced the ring and lid for the drum with a new one.
column170: The Veolia employee was retrained on the proper forklift operation and was reminded to inspect loads prior to moving them in any capacity.

column169: On January 26, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing UN3266 was crushed in transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site.  HCE personnel neutralized the corrosive impacted trailer using a water and citric acid solution.  After the dock trailer floor was neutralized, crews deployed granular absorbent to the impacted trailer. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. The 55-gallon drum was overpacked into one 95-gallon poly drum. All waste was then driven to the R+L terminal in Elgin, IL to be staged onsite for future disposal.

column169: On 1/5/24 at approximately 10:00 AM, Operators were loading ethanol from railcar MUI-X 730192 into Petroleum Carriers trailer 9301. While loading a scheduled 1400 gallons into compartment 2(capacity 2500 gallons), product was released from the overflow tubes at the rear of the trailer. The pump meter read 1272 gallons at the time of the release. An estimated 100 gallons impacted the asphalt. Product evaporated, there is no cleanup material to be disposed of. All appropriate personnel were notified of the incident. Overfill protection on the pump was disabled by the loaders. Driver failed to advise loaders that there was product remaining in the compartment being loaded.
column170: loaded. Overfill protection switches have been locked out on all pumps to prevent disabling by employees for any reason. Employees have been retrained to never bypass a safety device and to report all equipment problems it mangement immediately.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XGR experienced a UN2491 Bonderite L-GP 505 Corrosion Inhibitor release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of product released to an 8' x 10' area of the trailer floor and a 10' x 25' area of the asphalt dock as well as a catch basin. The release was due to a forklift puncture to the bottom of the drum. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were deployed to clean the impacted trailer floor and collected into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. A pressure washer and vac unit along with citric acid solution were then utilized to clean the impacted asphalt and catch basin. All impacted wastewater was placed into (7) 250-gallon poly totes. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: While offloading the trailer, a Veolia employee moved a drum inside a trailer by hand in order to align the drums so that he could grab the drums with drum grabber more easily. When he began to tilt one of the metal drums, he noticed that it was leaking from the bottom. He pushed the drum to its side to identify the leak and noticed multiple pin holes where material was leaking from. Due to the weight of the drum, the employee was unable to flip the drum by himself and sought assistance. With help, they were able to flipped the drum upside down to prevent further release of material from the drum. Approximately 30 gallons leaked out of the drum and into the unloading dock containment area. The damaged drum along with the 9 other drums from the same shipment were placed into a salvage drum.    The leaked liquid inside the trailer was absorbed and the liquid in the containment area was pumped out. The day before it was raining, so when the employee went inside of the trailer he did not see any visible signs of dripping or stains to show a possible leak. Nor did the employee see any abnormalities/ deficiencies to the drum before moving it. The actual duration of the spill is unknown however, Veolia believes that the spill occurred after the time of receiving into the facility since there was no evidence of any spill at our transfer location.
column170: As a refresher, Veolia informed employees to always inspect their surroundings and to verify the condition of the drums prior to handling of containers. In addition, Veolia does not believe the cause of the spill was in transportation but rather due to foreign substance that corroded and created the pinholes.  This is based on the location of the pinholes which appear to be a random/spray pattern, in addition it appears that the bottom paint was stripped by the material in question that caused the corrosion. This was the only drum that was green in color on the bottom of the drum while the remaining common drums that were shipped, were not that color.  All drums were new and not reconditioned, made by the same drum manufacturer. The pinholes show evidence the corrosion started from exterior of the container since the pinholes shows multiple layers from the outside.   Due to the corrosion occurring at the bottom of the drum, likely the drum was exposed prior to being filled and likely stored upside down. It was stored near or around materials that may be incompatible with metal drums. In addition, the material that was inside the drum had a pH value of 7 and the chemical composition did not reveal anything that would be a concern for corrosion on metal. Veolia has reached out to the offeror in regards to our findings in order to mitigate from future occurrence.

column169: On January 22, 2024, one (1) 500-pound cylinder of UN1009 was hissing when moved and covered in ice. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to inspect the cylinder and remediate the site. TLE personnel inspected the cylinder for any punctures or damage. No damage was found. Crews observed the cylinder was off gassing, creating a reaction. TLE personnel utilized hand tools, and absorbent pads, to remove ice from the frozen cylinder. Crews then moved the cylinder to the OS&D heat room, so the cylinder could gently warm up, and continue to release all of its contents. TLE personnel verified the cylinder released all of its contents and finished off gassing. Crews estimated 186 pounds of gas released. TLE personnel recommended the cylinder warm up a few hours before sending it for continued processing and shipping. All Ansul Halon 1301 (UN1009) impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 5-gallon pail and R+L personnel took possession of the waste to be added to the facility waste stream.

Transport was headed West on CR1077, when the vehicle failed to negotiate the curve that curved back South. Driver stated he looked away from the roadway to check on an empty water bottle, when his steer tire went over the shoulder. The driver decided not to correct the transport, striking trees and caution chevrons, overturning the transport and splitting the trailer in half on impact. The trailer released the entire load 154 barrels.   Safety was immediately dispatched from Coffeyville Resources to start clean up and remediation. The Kansas Highway Patrol was dispatched at the time of the incident, the road was diverted while the transport and trailer was towed. Clean up began on 01/21 but was delayed due to weather conditions (rain and ice). The soil has been dug up and transported to a landfill. The Coffeyville Resources Pipeline group hauled Vac trucks of the water used to keep the soil from continuing to be contaminated to the Coffeyville Refinery. The clean up was completed on 2/16.
column170: Driver responsible for the incident was terminated.  Training over the incident was and will be discussed in upcoming (2024) Safety Meetings with all CRCT drivers and staff.

The shipment consists 2 wooden pallets, each with 4 steel drums containing what appears to contain a hazardous materials.  Each drum displays the flammable globally harmonized symbol.  Dangerous Goods Administration obtained an online safety data sheet based the product name that is shown on the drum which identified the hazardous substance as UN 1268 Petroleum Distillates.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations and is bein held, pending at FAA investigation.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews observed that R+L had already overpacked the leaking pail, placed absorbents to the spill location. FCE personnel deployed a PH test to the unattended for areas reading a 12. column43: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column169: See attached document: Exhibit 1 01.13.2024 Release Incident Timeline  The 21 1/2" trailer dome lid was not secured. The dome lid is located top rear center of the trailer.  The release began sometime between 0841 and 0847. The release concluded at 0858. The remediation completed at 2200. (estimated 13h 20m)  A combination of dry sand and soda ash was spread over the release areas to neutralize the Sulfuric Acid. The debris was collected and placed in roll off containers for disposal.
column170: We are retraining all our drivers on pre-trip procedures. Specifically, tanker securement. We are in the process of issuing a policy, to be signed by all of our drivers, instructing them to close and secure all valves, caps, and dome lids before leaving any facility. Violation of which will result in discipline up to and including termination.  We are working closely with CHEMTRADE in Oregon, OH, to develop a driver loading/offloading audit program. The program will entail Roeder Cartage Company Inc. safety personnel to visually monitor our drivers loading/offloading at CHEMTRADE. The goal is to audit company drivers that load/offload at CHEMTRADE more frequently.  With the help of CHEMTRADE, we have created a loading check sheet for audit record keeping, and for our drivers to use as a reference. We are currently developing a similar check sheet for all products we load/offload.  We have no recommendations for improvements to hazardous material transportation beyond the control of our company, as this incident resulted from driver error.

Violation of which will result in discipline up to and including termination.  We are working closely with CHEMTRADE in Oregon, OH, to develop a driver loading/offloading audit program. The program will entail Roeder Cartage Company Inc. safety personnel to visually monitor our drivers loading/offloading at CHEMTRADE. The goal is to audit company drivers that load/offload at CHEMTRADE more frequently.  With the help of CHEMTRADE, we have created a loading check sheet for audit record keeping, and for our drivers to use as a reference. We are currently developing a similar check sheet for all products we load/offload.  We have no recommendations for improvements to hazardous material transportation beyond the control of our company, as this incident resulted from driver error.

column169: On January 10, 2024, two (2) 275-gallon totes of UN1866 were crushed in transit and released approximately 300-gallons of product to the trailer interior and adjacent freight. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the impacted site. HES personnel unloaded the trailer, wiping freight as it was being transferred out of the trailer. Crews then deployed absorbents to the paint thinner impacted trailer interior. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into 55-gallon drums for terminal disposal. HES transferred the remaining contents from the two (2) 275-gallon totes to one (1) new 275-gallon and two (2) 55-gallons drums. The damaged totes were cut into pieces and placed into two(55-gallon drums. HES removed seven (7) pallets that were damaged and/or impacted by the paint thinner. Additional damaged/impacted freight including aerosol cans of break cleaner and freon were removed and placed into 55-gallon drums for disposal. A total of 15 55-gallon drums of waste were generated and staged onsite for terminal disposal.

column169: FRA Hazmat Inspector Wolfe reported the TILX 306907 releasing an unknown amount of vapor.  UP Hazmat responded to the car.  Upon inspecting the car, the valve handles were able to be turned very slightly indicating they were in an open position.  The valve plugs were impacted with several layers of old teflon tape and thread dope which prohibited the plugs from being fully engaged and secured. There was also old teflon debris inside of the valve body and threaded faceplate. The handles were all closed, and the plugs were removed and cleaned. The debris was also removed from the valve body.  New teflon tape was applied to the threads and the plugs were secured tool tight.

column169: On January 4, 2024, six (6) one-gallon pails of UN1263 were forked and released approximately six (6) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the released product in the trailer and outside of the trailer and collected them with hand tools. HCE personnel then utilized universal absorbent pads to wipe down the impacted pallets and surfaces. One (1) 55-gallon drum that contained the six (6) damaged pails, and one (1) 55-gallon drum that contained impacted absorbents and debris were both labeled appropriately and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

column169: It was reported that approximately 10-15 gallons of battery acid released due to battery housing fault. The release impacted a 6’ X 2’ area on the asphalt underneath the trailer and trailer floor. No storm drains or waterways were reported to be impacted by the release. EnviroServe arrived on-site and neutralized the acid with a caustic material then deployed absorbents to solidify the release. The contractor collected and containerized the impacted batteries into 3-95-gallon poly drums and all clean-up debris into 1-55-gallon poly drums. The damaged batteries that were overpacked into 3–95-gallon poly DFs were secured inside the trailer for transit. EnviroServe departed the site with the 1–55-gallon poly drum and staged the waste at their office pending disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal LJS experienced a UN3286 EC1417A release from a 350-gallon metal tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5-gallons of product released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the trailer floor as well as the tote body. The lid to the tote was not secure causing a release. The tote and impacted trailer floor were wiped down and cleaned with simple green. All impacted pads and PPE were then placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The crew removed and cleaned the gasket which was then reseated, they then tightened the bolts and conducted a slosh test to ensure there would be no further release. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On January 16, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing UN3082 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer interior. GSSGI personnel deployed granular absorbents, cleaners and absorbent pads to the UN3082-impacted trailer interior/dock floor. All spent absorbents, absorbent pads, impacted shrink wrap, and cut up pallet were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged 55-gallon drum was containerized into one (1) 95-gallon over-pack. Both were set aside for terminal disposal.

column169: The tank car had a prior release while being switched in the yard because the pressure relief device broke and fell into the car on Dec17, 2023 (5800 report # 2023121166). The Haz Mat manager Tom Robinson put the car into a hold and told the yard manager to not move the car until a new valve was put onto the car. There was a bag applied to the missing PRD to protect the commodity. The car was moved to Englewood Yard and then back to Settegast where it was reported to be leaking again to Haz Mat manager Tom Robinson. During movement the product sloshed out underneath the bag that was covering the broken PRD. The car was set back onto the track it was originally in, and the Haz Mat Manager was assured it would not move again until the proper repairs made.

column169: On January 30, 2024, two (2) 55-gallon drums of UN1760 were leaking from the bungs and released approximately less than one (<1) cup of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Hazmat Services (EHS) to remediate the impacted site. Crews wiped down the released product with cleaners and absorbent pads. EHS personnel placed the damaged 55-gallon drum into one (1) 95-gallon poly overpack, and the one (1) undamaged 55-gallon drum and one (1) 95-gallon overpack were placed onto a pallet and gift wrapped for return to the terminal. Crews took one (1) poly liner of the absorbent pads and cleanup debris back to their shop.

On January 10, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN3098 was damaged during shipping and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel collected one (1) damaged 5-gallon pail of UN3098 and containerized it in one (1) 55-gallon drum. Crews then deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in using hand tools. FCE personnel utilized absorbent wipes to remediate any residual product. All UN3098 impacted material was collected and containerized in three (3) 55-gallon drums for disposal by R+L.

GrayMar Environmental Services was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2ft- by-2ft  area  of  the  concrete  trailer  yard  and  a  10ft-by-15ft  area  of  the  trailer  floor  and  estimated  that twenty (20) gallons of material was released due to a nail puncture from a pallet during offloading that damaged one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. GrayMar Environmental Services personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and recovered the spent material and containerized into one (1) 55- gallon metal drum. The damaged metal drum was over-packed into one (1) 65-gallon metal drum. The generated  waste  was  stage  onsite  at  the  terminal  in  a  secure  location  prior  to  the  contractor demobilization.  The  generated  waste  will  remain  onsite  for  the  ESTES  DGRM  team  to  coordinate disposal.

column169: This was the last pick up for the day and when the driver was doing his pick up the customer added more paint waste to the drum and he loaded it on his truck. The drive was about an hour back to the facility to unload for the end of the day. He arrive at approximately 1730 and when he opened the door to unload they noticed the drum was swelling up. The team at the facility emidiatly called for a team to come out and and address the container. The drum expanded to the point of failure at about 1830 before the team could arrive to address the situation. The bottom of the container failed and the contents was released into the truck with around 10 gallons making it to the pavement. They were able to contained it with absorbents and booms from spreading. The team arrived around 1930 to perform the clean up. They dawned the proper PPE and proceeded to clean up the material and overpacking the container to be shipped and disposed of properly. The crew was able to complete this around 2200.
column170: We believe that the paint waste that was added by the customer just before the driver picked up drum may have had an incompatible material in it which caused the reaction. The facility management team is working with the customer to figure out what was the added.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal UDV experienced a UN2929 Sulfix 9272 Scavenger release from (2) 330-gallon poly totes. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 70-gallons of product released to a 10’ x 10’ area of the trailer floor and a 20’ x 20’ area of the asphalt lot below. The totes were punctured by metal sticking out from the trailer wall. Each tote was transferred into two new totes for shipment on. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The impacted absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly, (3) 55-gallon metal, and (3) 95-gallon poly drums. The two damaged totes were then cut up and containerized into (1) 95-gallon poly and (1) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: SequenceEvent: The box was found in the Damages Area wet and torn open.  It did not have any hazardous markings, so I thought it was water/rain from that day.  However, I felt a burning sensation on my wrists and discovered the liquid was battery acid.  It was an undeclared HazMat and a SDS was found to confirm its hazardous status. DescribePack: The FedEx Office box was torn open and soiled.  There were plastic bags of plastic Christmas ornaments spilling out (inner packing).  There were also three Non-HazMat items inside, but they got battery acid on them.  The battery was inside a plastic shopping bag. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: I found a SDS for the battery despite being sent Standard Domestic Residential and lacking any hazardous indications on the box.  I isolated the package and processed it after knowing it was hazardous.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: On 1/5/2024, at approximately 1400, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 240946 at the station location in Spokane, reporting an undeclared battery sihpment.  The package contains an electric lawnmower, powered by lithium battery.  The package was orginally tendered with a UN 3481 marked on the package.  The shipment was rejected and the shipper was contracted for retrieval.  The shipper returned the shipment with the previous marking partially crossed out and declared the shipment unregulated.  Further investigation confirmed that the contents inside was indeed an electric lawnmover, packed with a lithium battery.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations.  The shipment is being held, pending an investgation by the FAA.
